[28 months later ...]

There is an engraved illustration almost exactly the same as this photo in the <i>Australian Town and Country Journal,</i> of 28/05/1887 p.27 (1119) - <a href="http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/page/5101442" rel="nofollow">trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/page/5101442</a> .  

The description reads - &quot;2. Observatory, <b>Bellevue Hill</b>, showing the Mode of Long-distance Surface Alignment by the Large Transit Instrument.&quot;

There is more detailed description of the sewer building  etc on p.9 (1101) - <a href="http://trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/71684105" rel="nofollow">trove.nla.gov.au/ndp/del/article/71684105</a> .   Including this description - &quot;Sketch No.2 shows the mode of fixing the centre line of the sewer on the surface by means of a transit instrument having a 3in object glass and a 34in focal length, and manufactured to order by Troughton and Sims, of London.&quot;

So, at Bellevue Hill (not North Bondi, <i>mea culpa</i>) and c.1887.  Or the Heritage site says 1885.
